JOHANNESBURG - President Jacob Zuma asked lawyer Ajay Sooklal, a confidante, not to testify at the commission into the arms deal to hide his dealings with a French arms company, the Sunday Times reports.Sooklal had "intimate knowledge" about how the president benefited from the arms deal, the paper says.Sooklal has disclosed the information in his affidavit supporting a high court application by Corruption Watch and the Right2Know campaign contesting the findings of the Seriti commission of inquiry into the arms deal.Background: here's @Corruption_SA & R2K's legal challenge to Seriti Commission's findings on the Arms Deal (Oct'16): https://t.co/R94gCkt3jKFor more on the story watch the video above.eNCA